"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"It isn’t every day that writer Philip Ball is asked to contribute to scientific experiments — typically, he’s reporting on them instead. But in 2015, scientists from a London-based project called Created Out of Mind asked Ball and a few other creatives if they’d participate in their work and then reflect on the experience. He agreed. ","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"nodeType":"insticator","data":{},"marks":[]},{"data":{},"content":[{"data":{},"marks":[],"value":"Ball first gave a sample, made up of cells from his skin, which was reprogrammed into stem cells that were subsequently grown into a brain organoid — or, as the research team called it, a miniature “brain in a dish.” These futuristic-sounding specimens aren’t literal brains, and they don’t look it, either. The round, cream-colored clusters of neurons simply resemble little blobs. They’re not conscious. But they can be studied to better understand brain development — such as where and when certain proteins misfold, which can signal whether a person will develop dementia. ","nodeType":"text"}],"nodeType":"paragraph"},{"data":{"target":{"metadata":{"tags":[]},"sys":{"space":{"sys":{"type":"Link","linkType":"Space","id":"cnu0m8re1exe"}},"id":"2mNi7TDqTv5mm96e69zZoo","type":"Asset","createdAt":"2020-05-11T17:34:44.454Z","updatedAt":"2020-05-14T18:10:57.371Z","environment":{"sys":{"id":"master","type":"Link","linkType":"Environment"}},"revision":2,"locale":"en-US"},"fields":{"title":"Microscope Images of Cells","description":"This stained microscope image shows cells growing in a cross-section of a brain organoid, with neurons visible in red. (Credit: Chris Lovejoy and Selina Wray)\n","file":{"url":"//images.ctfassets.net/cnu0m8re1exe/2mNi7TDqTv5mm96e69zZoo/d48fdaba050546adaa896a2a45ec7bdf/Slice1.jpg","details":{"size":21349,"image":{"width":500,"height":381}},"fileName":"Slice1.jpg","contentType":"image/jpeg"}}}},"content":[],"nodeType":"embedded-